```

> And based on `OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_PLATFORM_KEY_REFERENCES_ENABLE`, either one of them will be invalid. It is up to the Crypto platform abstraction to use the correct member based on the implementation supported.

I am not sure if this is a good approach/model (even if it may work for now with the current platform implementation). 
I would recommend not using it.
- In the definition of `otCryptoKey` we have that `mKeyRef` is valid only when `mKey` is `NULL`, which would not be case here: 
```c++
struct otCryptoKey
{
    const uint8_t *mKey;       ///< Pointer to the buffer containing key. NULL indicates to use `mKeyRef`.
    uint16_t       mKeyLength; ///< The key length in bytes (applicable when `mKey` is not NULL).
    uint32_t       mKeyRef;    ///< The PSA key ref (requires `mKey` to be NULL).
};
```
- Basically I think here we are not  following the documentation of how `otCryptoKey` should be used by platform layer (and can set `mKey` as a non-`NULL` even when we intend to use `mKeyRef` and then expect platform layer to be aware of `OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_PLATFORM_KEY_REFERENCES_ENABLE` config and use it instead to deterime whethere to use `mKey` or `mKeyRef`).
- I think it is better to not assume that platform layer code would see the same set of OT configs. The `OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_PLATFORM_KEY_REFERENCES_ENABLE` is really only intended for the OT core.
- I notice that in the code from the PR in other places, we follow the pattern of setting `mKey` to `nullptr` when we want to use `mKeyRef`. For example we have this patten in a few places in `key_manager` (e.g., in `ComputeKeys()` and `ComputeTrelKey()`)
```c++
void KeyManager::ComputeKeys(uint32_t aKeySequence, HashKeys &aHashKeys)
{
    Crypto::HmacSha256 hmac;
    uint8_t            keySequenceBytes[sizeof(uint32_t)];
    otCryptoKey        aKeyMaterial;

#if OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_PLATFORM_KEY_REFERENCES_ENABLE
    aKeyMaterial.mKey    = nullptr;
    aKeyMaterial.mKeyRef = mNetworkKeyRef;
#else
    aKeyMaterial.mKey       = mNetworkKey.m8;
    aKeyMaterial.mKeyLength = sizeof(mNetworkKey.m8);
    aKeyMaterial.mKeyRef    = 0;
#endif
```
- I think it may be better to be consistent and use the same pattern everywhere.

