Just to clarify, with AWS Chalice it'll typically be an object (class instance), not a class reference. For example with this code snippet:
```
# app.py
from chalice.app import Chalice

app = Chalice(__name__)
```
The Lambda handler module would be `app.app`. That being said though, technically all 3 of the following options are valid callables:
```
# app.py
from typing import Any


class StaticMeta(type):
    @staticmethod
    def __call__(event: dict[str, Any], context: Any) -> dict[str, str]:
        return {"hello": f"from {StaticMeta = }"}


class ClassMeta(type):
    @classmethod
    def __call__(cls, event: dict[str, Any], context: Any) -> dict[str, str]:
        return {"hello": f"from {cls = }"}


class StaticHandler(metaclass=StaticMeta):
    pass


class ClassHandler(metaclass=ClassMeta):
    pass


class InstanceHandler:
    @classmethod
    def __call__(self, event: dict[str, Any], context: Any) -> dict[str, str]:
        return {"hello": f"from {self = }"}


handler1 = StaticHandler
handler2 = ClassHandler
handler3 = InstanceHandler()
```
With the Lambda handler modules being `app.handler1`, `app.StaticHandler`, `app.handler2`, `app.ClassHandler` and `app.handler3`.

