Okay, on thinking a bit more I guess a simpler formulation is


```rust
impl<T: Hash + Eq> Filter<T> {
    fn pluck<'f, 'm: 'f, V: 'm>(
        &'f self,
        it: impl Iterator<Item = (&'m T, &'m V)> + 'm,
    ) -> impl Iterator<Item = (&'m T, &'m V)> + 'f
    where
        T: Eq + Hash + 'm,
    {
        let which: Option<&'f HashSet<T>> = match self {
            Filter::All => None,
            Filter::Just(which) => Some(which),
        };
        it.filter(move |(k, _)| match which {
            None => true,
            Some(which) => which.contains(k),
        })
    }
}
```

which should about have the same runtime properties as what I sketched
above: the `match self` on `Either::next` in that version corresponds to
the `match which` in the `it.filter` closure in this one.

So less complicated (almost fits on a screen), but the lifetime
annotations are still a bit much. But I could at least reasonably be
convinced now. Let me know if you have any thoughts.

